name: Agaricomycetes_Varga2019
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock and speed dating on fixed topology (RAxML + PhyloBayes + FastDate)
Notes: This is only one of the 10 different ML trees on which this dating approach was applied

name: Anthophila_HenriquezPiskulich
Notes: All 4,586 bee species tree converted to dated chronogram with treePL, including ufbs node support values. Outgroups removed.

name: Asteraceae_Palazzesi2022
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock + grafting on backbone tree (RevBayes)

name: Caryophyllales_Smithetal2017_align_w_shtest_treepl_3samp
Notes: align_w_shtest_treepl_3samp.tre = maximum likelihood tree with divergence time estimation and 3 minimum samples

name: Charadriiformes_Cerny2022
Notes: Tree topology estimated with total-evidence (molecules + morphology) dataset; 19 species have only morphological data

name: Cichlidae_McGee2020
Notes: 1015 tips (59%) have molecular data associated with them. It is not entirely clear how the remaining species have been grafted into the tree: "implementing topological constraints from previous phylogenomic studies of smaller clades"

name: Ericaceae_Schwery2015
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock on fixed topology (RAxML + BEAST)

name: Hyloidea_Hutter2017
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock + grafting on backbone tree (BEAST2)
Notes: Relative timetrees for each family estimated and then grafted on a backbone; absolute time tree produced with just few taxa per family

name: Lissamphibia_Jetz2018
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock on fixed topology plus taxonomic grafting (EML-RAxML + MrBayes + PASTIS)
Notes: 4061 species have molecular data, 3177 species only have taxonomic assignment

name: Mammalia_AlvarezCarretero2022
Tree-building/dating approach: Sequential Bayesian dating with approximate likelihood (MCMCtree)
Notes: Tree has been rescaled to million years unit, originally it was scaled down by a factor of 100

name: Melastomataceae_Reginato2020
Notes: Age constraints for penalized likelihood taken from relaxed Bayesian clock analysis (BEAST2) with only few taxa

name: Mimosa_Vasconcelos2020
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock on fixed topology (BEAST)
Notes: Fixed tree and molecular sequences taken from previous study (Simon et al 2011) and time-calibrated

name: Monocots_Howard2019
Notes: This tree looks a bit weird, it has huge 'rakes' of many species diverging in a super short time (almost like artificially resolved polytomies): probably it is not ideal for the analysis of branch lengths over time

name: Orobanchaceae_Mortimer2022
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock on fixed topology (BEAST)
Notes: Methods not entirely clear because I did not have access to the paper; the supplements include two different output trees, one "Fu_Calibrated", the other "Schneider_Calibrated"; the tree uploaded here is the "Fu_Calibrated"

name: Phasmatodea_Bank2022
Notes: Some topological constraints applied based on previous literature (B2 constraints set in paper).

name: Pinophyta_Leslie2018
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed(?) Bayesian clock on fixed topology (RAxML + BEAST)
Notes: Gnetophyta, a bizarre group with around 70 species not included in this study, could potentially cluster within Pinophyta (the clade considered here) as sister to Pinales

name: Poaceae_Spriggs2015
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock + grafting on backbone tree (BEAST)
Notes: Two calibration scenarios are used in the paper. This is the resulting tree for calibration scenario #1

name: Polemoniaceae_Landis2018
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock on fixed topology (RAxML + BEAST)
Notes: Not all tips are recognized species, 82 of them are currently classified as subspecies

name: Polemoniaceae_Rose2021
Notes: Not all tips are recognized species, but number of subspecies is not specified in the paper

name: Polypodiophyta_Lehtonen2017
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock with ML-informed topological constraint (RAxML + BEAST2)
Notes: Nodes with > 0.9 bootstrap support in RAxML tree are fixed in the BEAST2 analysis

name: Polypodiophyta_Nitta2022
Notes: Version 1.4.0 of the Fern Tree of Life

name: Polypodiophyta_Testo2016
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock on fixed topology (RAxML + BEAST2)

name: Primates_Springer2012
Tree-building/dating approach: Maximum likelihood (RAxML), time tree with autocorrelated rates and soft-bounded constraints

name: Rhopalocera_Kawahara2023
Tree-building/dating approach: Gene tree estimation => IQ-TREE species tree estimation => divergence time estimation using treePL
Notes: High genus coverage (92%), not so high species coverage. Taxa are sampled with the aim of covering the higher taxonomic diversity

name: Russulaceae_Hackel2022
Notes: Tree has been rescaled to million years unit, originally it was scaled down such as that its height was equal to 1; tips represent clustering of sequence pool including undescribed species and environmental samples, as well as described species

name: Salvia_Kriebel2019
Tree-building/dating approach: Relaxed Bayesian clock with ML-informed topological constraint (RAxML + BEAST2)

name: Squamata_Tonini2016
Tree-building/dating approach: PASTIS. Maximum likelihood (RAxML), Divergence times with MrBayes 3.2

name: Vascular_Plants_Zanne2014
Notes: mostly angiosperms. they claim over 32k taxa for some reason.
